{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"09fc510f-3e8b-42f9-b417-bf71c00539e3","content":"Use **`dotnet-trace`** — it's the lightest option that works well inside containers.\n\n### Steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the pod\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (default provider is fine for CPU)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n### Getting the file out\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Tips\n\n- **No SDK needed** — `dotnet-trace` works with just the runtime.\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, download the [standalone binary](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#install-as-a-global-tool).\n- For **native + managed** stacks (e.g., GC or JIT overhead), use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling --clrevents gc+jit` or switch to **`perf`** / `dotnet-counters` for a quick triage first.\n- Add `--format speedscope` to get a JSON file you can open at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app) without any tooling.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60712ffe-81f7-47a4-b53d-5bafd3d18195","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"2159:3AA73:5D4A94D:660FD31:69F00D12"},"id":"454eb580-2dfb-44ed-9e71-c148da1fee33","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:27:57.767Z","parentId":"90e670e5-197d-426f-a286-6384244c1eea"}
